⁣
𝗪𝗶𝗹𝗱𝗹𝗶𝗳𝗲 𝗠𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁⁣
⁣
Predator hunting is a necessity, though I've never been much of a predator hunter.⁣
⁣
I eat what I hunt, which curbs any desire to pursue something that isn't pleasant on the plate. Mountain Lion meat just happens to be delicious.⁣
⁣
As a proponent of science-based wildlife management, when the opportunity to help control a growing population meets the crossroad of bringing home nutritious meals - I am elated to play my part.⁣
⁣
The Tom quota being closed in my area was a relief. ⁣
⁣
Everyone wants a big Tom. ⁣
I was ecstatic to take this female with my bow.⁣
⁣
When discussing population control, I can't continue to stress this enough, breeding-age females (𝘪𝘯 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘷𝘢𝘴𝘵 𝘮𝘢𝘫𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘵𝘺 𝘰𝘧 𝘩𝘶𝘯𝘵𝘦𝘥 𝘴𝘱𝘦𝘤𝘪𝘦𝘴) control the population.⁣
⁣
•I'm grateful for this cat. ⁣
⁣
•I'm grateful for my incredible partner and his unbelievable skill and experience in the backcountry. ⁣
⁣
•I'm grateful for our determined hounds who never missed a step, even in the bitter cold and often chest-deep snow and deadfall.⁣
⁣
•I'm grateful for the meals already enjoyed by our family.⁣
⁣
Here's to my final tag of 2022.⁣
⁣

⁣
𝗪𝗼𝗿𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗗𝗼𝗴𝘀⁣
⁣
Last night, the temperatures dipped to dangerous lows. We have six rambunctious hounds who are tough in ways I’ll never understand. They would have hunkered down in their insulated dog boxes and been fine in their outdoor kennels - but we weren’t fine knowing they’d be so cold.⁣
⁣
They spent the night and today as inside dogs.⁣
⁣
I can only imagine how claustrophobic they must have felt spending a night indoors. It’s not their usual haunt. However, a big fatty meal, treats, and a cozy bed have more than been earned.⁣
⁣
They are more than working dogs - ⁣
they are loved.⁣
⁣
While the bird dogs get constant cuddles and fill our beds with felted fur- these hardworking hounds don’t get enough love, and I’m going to be better at showing them my appreciation more often.⁣
⁣
Patch and Jackie braved blistering cold and never waivered while treeing my lion this year. Perle Haggard wasn’t too far behind, doing her best.⁣
⁣
They’ve earned more respect than most dogs are ever offered.⁣
⁣
It smells 𝘩𝘰𝘳𝘳𝘪𝘧𝘪𝘤 downstairs and their slightly uncomfortable bays at being indoors are on the verge of annoying AF while I work- ⁣
⁣
but they are warm,⁣
and they are loved.⁣
⁣
-And I will bundle up gladly to bring them treats and let them run today before tucking them back into their cozy vacation bed.⁣
⁣
Goll dang it, they’ve bayed their way into my little black heart.⁣

⁣
𝟮𝟬𝟮𝟯⁣
⁣
We rang in the New Year with 𝘱𝘦𝘳𝘵𝘯𝘦𝘢𝘳 30 friends, all packed into our little abode.⁣
⁣
We enjoyed homemade crab rangoons, egg rolls, bison chili, a bumbpin’ 𝘴𝘏𝘢𝘙-𝘬𝘰𝘰-𝘵𝘊𝘩𝘦𝘦 board, and shredded bbq mountain lion sliders from this cat.⁣
⁣
The empty bottles, random sprigs of broccoli in every corner, and confetti-a-plenty confirmed a good time was had.⁣
⁣
Some experienced a markedly higher quantity of “good times” than others. ⁣
⁣
To them I give a nod, a toast, and a hope that by now, your headache has subsided.⁣
⁣
Here’s to another flip-O’-the-calendar.⁣

⁣
These pups have been on my mind the past few days.⁣
⁣
All these airports-⁣
and trade shows-⁣
and dinners-⁣
and schmoozing…⁣
⁣
I find myself wishing I was anywhere but here.⁣
⁣
Mostly, I find myself wishing I was home in the company of these pups. They’re twice the hunters most of the people I’ll be in the company of are. ⁣
⁣
They truly do it for the love of it. It’s in their blood. It’s their sole purpose. ⁣
⁣
I think a lot of the hunting industry could stand to learn more about being a true hunter from a good dog.⁣
⁣
This old girl teaching this young pup how to work a cat into a tree is worthy of more clout than most of the hunters signing autographs.⁣
⁣
I think a return to the basics is something that might be needed for a lot of the hot air I’ve been swimming through this week. I’ve been grateful to be reunited with old friends and faces, but aside from that, the “show” is exhausting.⁣
⁣
But what do I know?⁣
⁣
I’m just a worthless huntress. 💅⁣
⁣
#airportmusings ⁣

⁣
𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗖𝘂𝗿𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝘁𝗲 𝗼𝗳 𝗧𝗵𝗲 “𝗜𝗡𝗗𝗨𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗬” ⁣
⁣
𝘈𝘳𝘦 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘨𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘵𝘰 𝘴𝘪𝘵 𝘵𝘩𝘦𝘳𝘦 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘣𝘦𝘭𝘪𝘦𝘷𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘧𝘢𝘤𝘵𝘴, 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘤𝘰𝘶𝘳𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘤𝘶𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘴, 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘯𝘦𝘸𝘴, 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘤𝘩𝘢𝘳𝘨𝘦𝘴, 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘱𝘶𝘣𝘭𝘪𝘤 𝘳𝘦𝘤𝘰𝘳𝘥𝘴, 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘰𝘸𝘯 𝘦𝘺𝘦𝘴 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘴…⁣
⁣
…𝘰𝘳 𝘢𝘳𝘦 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘨𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦𝘭𝘪𝘦𝘷𝘦 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝙄 𝘵𝘦𝘭𝘭 𝘺𝘰𝘶?⁣
⁣
𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵’𝘴 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘐 𝘵𝘩𝘰𝘶𝘨𝘩𝘵.⁣
⁣
𝘓𝘪𝘬𝘦 • 𝘴𝘶𝘣𝘴𝘤𝘳𝘪𝘣𝘦 •⁣
𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘥𝘢𝘯𝘤𝘦, 𝘮𝘰𝘯𝘬𝘦𝘺 • 𝘿𝘼𝙉𝘾𝙀.⁣
🏹💪🏻⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
I’d like to believe a few of us are still left sitting around the fire while the confused masses jump up and dance on command.⁣
⁣
I’m just not so sure anymore.⁣
⁣
⁣
Photo: Me - because that’s what feeds the algorithm, right?⁣

⁣
I never thought I’d have this many dogs, and still think I need more.⁣
⁣
Annie has been the auntie dog to all the new pups, and since she’s getting older, it’s time for her to adopt one of her own.⁣
⁣
Enough huntin’ hounds.⁣
⁣
It’s time for the bird dog population in our colony to increase. ⁣
⁣
📸: Perle Haggard and Annie

⁣
𝗪𝗿𝗮𝗽𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘂𝗽 𝗝𝗮𝗻𝘂𝗮𝗿𝘆 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗯𝗶𝗴 𝗴𝗼𝗮𝗹𝘀 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝟮𝟬𝟮𝟯.⁣
⁣
It’s been a hectic month. Trade shows (which aren’t over yet), crazy weather, website upgrades, and planning until my planner is plum planned - ⁣
⁣
I’m tired…⁣
⁣
but excited.⁣
⁣
This year is going to be about growth in all aspects, from personal growth to professional growth and everything in between.⁣
⁣
I want to leave this year better than I found it, and I think I’ve got a helluva start.⁣
⁣
I’m getting this flat-ass in shape. ⁣
⁣
I’m working on being the best version of myself that I can be.⁣
⁣
I’m setting crazy work goals and smashing the shit out of them.⁣
⁣
I’m refusing to lessen myself for those around me and flat denying to set my morals aside for clout.⁣
⁣
2023 will have a tone of authenticity and badassery. Period. ⁣
⁣
*𝘐’𝘥 𝘢𝘵𝘵𝘦𝘮𝘱𝘵 𝘵𝘰 𝘪𝘯𝘴𝘦𝘳𝘵 𝘴𝘰𝘮𝘦 𝘩𝘪𝘱 𝘱𝘩𝘳𝘢𝘴𝘦 𝘩𝘦𝘳𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘬𝘪𝘥𝘴 𝘶𝘴𝘦 𝘯𝘰𝘸𝘢𝘥𝘢𝘺𝘴 𝘴𝘰 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘐 𝘴𝘰𝘶𝘯𝘥 𝘤𝘰𝘰𝘭, 𝘣𝘶𝘵 𝘪𝘵’𝘴 𝘨𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘩𝘢𝘳𝘥. ⁣
𝘐’𝘮 𝘨𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘧𝘶𝘳𝘵𝘩𝘦𝘳 𝘰𝘶𝘵 𝘰𝘧 𝘵𝘰𝘶𝘤𝘩. 𝘕𝘰 𝘤𝘢𝘱.⁣
⁣

⁣
Though I’m certainly happy for the guy who watched this buck fall after a squeeze of the trigger, I can’t help but feel a little heartbroken that my days of watching him are over.⁣
⁣
The emotions I experience with the life and death of these animals are so varied, confusing, and often overwhelming. It’s hard to describe an immense joy that can be felt simultaneously with sorrow.⁣
⁣
I think hunters understand that strange dichotomy more than most. We enjoy watching these animals live their lives, and then - we choose their last day. ⁣
⁣
It’s a strange roller coaster of elation meets devastation. It isn’t until you make that conscious choice to take the life of something you love that you can ever truly understand that.⁣
⁣
I’m grateful for the countless days I was able to watch him through the years, and damnit - ⁣
⁣
I feel an intense sorrow knowing he won’t grace the field next fall.⁣
⁣
Thanks for the memories, Big 5.⁣

75° days on white sands are neat.⁣
⁣
A Tarpon flying at the end of my line is indescribable.⁣
⁣
…but my cold, black heart belongs on the cold, white tundra.⁣
⁣

⁣
𝗗𝗲𝗮𝗱𝗹𝘆 𝗜𝗻𝗻𝗼𝘃𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 ⁣
𝗔𝗰𝗰𝘂𝗯𝗹𝗮𝗱𝗲™ 𝗕𝗿𝗼𝗮𝗱𝗵𝗲𝗮𝗱𝘀 ⁣
⁣
Everyone throws around phrases like:⁣
⁣
“𝘎𝘢𝘮𝘦 𝘊𝘩𝘢𝘯𝘨𝘪𝘯𝘨”⁣
“𝘎𝘳𝘰𝘶𝘯𝘥𝘣𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘬𝘪𝘯𝘨”⁣
 ⁣
…but when @noslerinc made the leap into bowhunting, they jumped hard and shattered the damn ground.⁣
⁣
The decision to partner with master bladesmith, @joshsmithknives of @montanaknifecompany brought indestructible, 𝘝𝘢𝘭𝘺𝘳𝘪𝘢𝘯 𝘚𝘵𝘦𝘦𝘭™ blades and unsurpassed craftsmanship.⁣
⁣
Partnering with @hoytbowhunting - ⁣
well, because bowhunting.⁣
⁣
The only odd piece of this puzzle is me, but I’m humbled and truly honored to find myself on the Nosler Archery Team.⁣
⁣
This could be the first true innovation of bowhunting tech in decades, and I’m not sure the tradition will ever be the same.⁣
⁣
With the way things are going in Montana lately, I’ll probably be able to launch one of these bad boys with a crossbow, wearing night vision, hanging out of a helicopter, at feral hogs in the Bob Marshall Wilderness before 2023 wraps. ⁣
⁣
Now, if I can only convince them to make a 200 grain, dual-blade, single bevel on a pretty little .270 copper jacket with a green polymer tip… ⁣
⁣
A girl can dream.⁣

⁣
I’m ready for hazy warm days and the frustration that I’m sure will find us in the bird grass this summer and early fall.⁣
⁣
Dogs are better than people, and I’m itching to spend more time afield with the better of the hunting partners.⁣
⁣
I have a feeling little Charlie will be a bird hunting machine.⁣

⁣
I smile a helluva lot less than I used to.⁣
⁣
I've got all these sun spots, smile lines, and crow's feet that I've earned but don't seem to be using as much these days. ⁣
⁣
After roundabouts four decades of circling the dang sun, I ain’t about to trade in smile-line-building for scowling.⁣
⁣
I think this stretch has been a combination of both circumstance and perspective. ⁣
⁣
The past week or so has been a real wake-up call, capped by an emotionally draining weekend... at best.⁣
⁣
An unexpected loss of young life and an unexpected injury that could have resulted in another loss of life - has rocked me a bit. ⁣
⁣
My foundation feels wobbly. ⁣
⁣
Life is fleeting.⁣
⁣
I was served a solid reminder of that fact; a reminder that felt like a bare-buckle punch to the jaw.⁣
⁣
It's time to stop doing so much floating through each day and get back to living then with more purpose.⁣
⁣
It's time to get my dirtbag setup back into my truck bed so I can spend a few more nights waking up on the river.⁣
⁣
It's time I start actively planning to do the things that make me smile with the humans that make those smiles come easier. ⁣
⁣
I've got a whole lot more wrinkles to earn.⁣
⁣
Life can be a real sumbitch, but so can I.⁣
⁣

⁣
📸: @savannah.406 - a human that is responsible for like 90% of my smiles and scowls. What a gem.

⁣
𝗟𝗶𝗳𝗲 𝗟𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗼𝗻𝘀⁣
⁣
These past few weeks have had their ups and downs. The downs just seem to be in season.⁣
⁣
From medical dismay to family disarray, loss of life and loss of crop, professional hassle and personal hurt: this stretch has been for the birds.⁣
⁣
I've learned that making responsible choices doesn't always result in health.⁣
⁣
I've learned that giving unfettered benefit-of-the-doubt often leads to little benefit and big doubt.⁣
⁣
I've learned that life just ends, often unexpectedly and always guaranteed. ⁣
⁣
I've learned that dogs continue to gain points over people, every single time.⁣
⁣
I've learned that kindness isn't always reciprocated and often is instead met with unexpected defense.⁣
⁣
I've learned that family bonds are only as strong as the people on each end choose them to be.⁣
⁣
Man... I've learned.⁣
⁣
Fortunately, I've been given a bit of clarity through it all. ⁣
⁣
I'm not choosing to be bitter. I'm choosing to reserve the kindness I extend to those who reflect it right back.⁣
⁣
I'm not choosing to fold. I'm choosing to take the hand I've been dealt and run with a poker face that is unmatched.⁣
⁣
I'm choosing to tell the people I love that I love them, even if they don't have it in them to say it back. ⁣
⁣
I'm choosing to close up the circle. Applications are closed. Budget cuts mean running a tight ship. I don't need more friends, and the friends I have are officially under audit. ⁣
⁣
I'm choosing to spend more time with dogs and less time with people, more time on the river and less time on the phone, more time under the stars and less time under the roof.⁣
⁣
Most of all, I'm choosing kindness because I've never been mean, and I refuse to build callouses where softness has always been.⁣
⁣
There's beauty in apathy where apathy is needed. My care will just be more directed, my effort more targeted.⁣
⁣
Plus, look at that face. When the world seems to be scowling at me from all directions, she just looks at me with wonder and reminds me that none of it really matters.⁣
⁣
We're just a couple of specks on a big old rock floating in space - and we're gonna laugh, love, and experience as much of it as we can while we're here.

⁣
𝗕𝗲𝗮𝗿𝘀⁣
⁣
It’s funny how little I think about bears anymore. I’ve been reminded of them this week for a few little reasons.⁣
⁣
A move and a change of career have dropped my bear interactions drastically.⁣
⁣
There were stretches where I’d sit and watch two or three grizzlies a week, some weeks more, some less. I was lucky to work in a career that surrounded me with them.⁣
⁣
I’ve had spooky run-ins where things were far too close for comfort, and every time, I was at fault and just got lucky. A few of which I don’t know that I’d be so lucky today.⁣
⁣
Now, I see a trail cam photo of a griz on occasion, but that’s the extent of my interaction with them. I’ve certainly gotten more and more relaxed in my stretches of wood.⁣
⁣
Outside the black bears we’ve glassed or treed during spring bear season this year, I can’t say I even see many bears anymore. They just aren’t a central feature of my current life, and I hadn’t really considered how much of a role they played until this past week.⁣
⁣
I do miss them in a weird way, but I think I’m content not really being concerned with what’s glassing elk with me on the hillside.⁣
⁣
I do love this country, and I miss the challenge of it, but I’m content with a visit to touch base and an easy return home. ⁣
⁣
Looking over from Big Sky at the ridges we used to play in makes me wonder if I’ve gotten soft or if I really started off that dumb.⁣
⁣
I think I’ll go with the latter.⁣
⁣
⁣
📸: A mamma and cubs I stumbled into unexpectedly who couldn’t have cared less about my existence while hiking a few years back… not terribly far from where I sit now.

⁣
…and reminiscing about the crazy old bear days after a trip near my old stomping grounds certainly reminded me of this last-minute adventure, a handful of years ago.⁣
⁣
Did we accomplish the mission? No.⁣
⁣
(𝘐 𝘮𝘦𝘢𝘯, 𝘑𝘰𝘳𝘥𝘢𝘯 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘶𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 𝘧𝘰𝘶𝘯𝘥 𝘸𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘸𝘦 𝘸𝘦𝘳𝘦 𝘭𝘰𝘰𝘬𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘧𝘰𝘳)⁣
⁣
Did we give it a helluva shot? Damn Skippy.⁣
⁣
Did we leave the mountains wreaking of bear stink? Fo sho.⁣
⁣
Did we die? Not quite but damn close. Too. Damn. Close.⁣
⁣
Here’s to trips with friends that imprint memories on places and stains in your britches.⁣
⁣

⁣
After this recent stretch of tough luck and bummed-out mentality, this weekend was so needed.⁣
⁣
I couldn't hit 𝘚𝘏𝘭𝘛 on the course. Picked up my bow from the shop 24 hours prior and didn't have a single pin set. Just let 'em rip for the hell of it. It was actually more fun than you'd think. I may be the only person who sights in their bow after TAC.⁣
⁣
Aside from that, it felt like a family reunion. ⁣
⁣
There were so many faces I've missed. I may have racked up more hugs in the past 72 hours than I have in the past 72 weeks. There's something to be said about a room filled with people who throw up their hands with a welcoming '𝗛𝗘𝗬𝗬𝗬𝗬𝗬' when you walk in. ⁣
⁣
That is officially my drug of choice.⁣
⁣
It was like this event took 80% of the people I adore and jammed them into one spot. I felt big love. ⁣
⁣
I was surrounded by incredible humans, my dearest friends, and I even added a few new names to the roster.⁣
⁣
The @noslerinc crew, @madiiiwoodward and @john.tnason , are some of my favorite people, and I was so glad to get some solid time with them both. Can't wait to see the again.⁣
⁣
@joshsmithknives , @brandon_horoho , @jessismithknifewife , and the entire @montanaknifecompany family were so welcoming, and it is so humbling to watch the community they are building.⁣
⁣
@jockowillink made me feel like a wimpy-little-girl-child, in the best way possible. ⁣
⁣
There are just too many people that I was so fortunate to share space with. So many laughs were had and new memories made.⁣
⁣
I was excited to get home but already feel homesick for the place and faces I just left.⁣
⁣
My heart is full.⁣
⁣

⁣
Obviously, I get spooked on occasion hiking out. I think everyone does when your mind starts playing tricks on you, and you're at the mercy of whatever is just on the other side of the dark. Nature doesn't play nice, and the reality is that we're part of it. It can be spooky. Every twig snap becomes a monster, you know?⁣

⁣

𝗠𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗮 𝗔𝗿𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘆 𝗕𝘂𝗰𝗸 𝟮𝟬𝟮𝟯⁣
⁣
After a long season of travel, work, and hunting out of state, the clock was running out on filling my Montana tags and my Montana freezers.⁣
⁣
I went out after work to sit a treestand in the hope of beating the does to the creek for the evening, my first sit of the Montana whitetail rut. ⁣
⁣
In a pair of canvas overalls and rubber boots, I shuffled my tail up the sketchiest tree to a stand that made me question both my sanity and the life choices that led me there.⁣
⁣
Not 20 minutes into settling in, a lone doe came in behind me from the right. I turned to watch her, waiting for her to come into my minimal-at-best shooting lane. ⁣
⁣
Then, this buck charged in from the left, trotting through rough brush before easing to a halt, maybe 15 yards from the base of the tree. I shifted my weight from right to left and my aim toward him. ⁣
⁣
He mozied, turned broadside, and I drew back. His front-facing leg took one step forward while he grazed, and I let my arrow go.⁣
⁣
It's the first time I've ever had a buck duck my arrow. ⁣
⁣
What would have been a perfect shot (I can only assume) hit high, just above the shoulder blade...⁣
but sunk 𝘥𝘦𝘦𝘱.⁣
⁣
He bucked hard and made a run back toward where he came from. ⁣
⁣
I knew I wanted to give him time. After jumping a deer last year, I couldn't stomach a repeat. ⁣
After maybe 45 minutes, I climbed out of the tree and retreated home to finish a bit of work and coerce my dragging partner to come back out with me.⁣
⁣
Right at dark, we returned and found him. He wasn't much more than 80 yards from my stand, and he didn't need the time I'd given him. It was clear he ran behind me, laid down, and died - all in quick succession.⁣
⁣
There were no fancy cameras, no fanfare, no sponsorships or obligations, just a strong-as-an-ox packout partner, a cold night, and a tag punched to fill the freezer for the coming year.⁣
⁣
I’m grateful for the human who not only accompanied me to find him, but also hoisted him over his shoulders to cross a creek.⁣
⁣
I’m grateful for a quick death that rattled my nerves for a moment.⁣
⁣
I’m grateful for this animal and the meals he’ll provide.⁣

𝗪𝗼𝗹𝘃𝗲𝘀⁣
⁣
If I had a nickel for every message in the past 48 hours that inquired about my feelings on the Colorado wolf reintroduction, I’d have at least a  few nickels.⁣
⁣
Not so long ago, a big part of my paycheck came from me knowing where the Yellowstone packs were and being able to find them. Wolves have played a big part in my life.⁣
⁣
I guess that gives my opinion some weight, at least in the eyes of some people, but here’s the thing: When asking me what my opinion is about the new Colorado wolves, I want to make one thing painfully clear:⁣
⁣
MY OPINION SHOULDN’T MATTER.⁣
⁣
And THAT really is the root of the problem. ⁣
⁣
I believe in the power of the vote. I believe the people of our country should have the final say in so many things. This is not one of them. ⁣
⁣
𝗕𝗮𝗹𝗹𝗼𝘁 𝗕𝗼𝘅 𝗕𝗶𝗼𝗹𝗼𝗴𝘆 𝗶𝘀 𝘄𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗴.⁣
⁣
It’s on par with letting my community vote on whether or not I should start taking a new medication my doctor prescribed. ⁣
⁣
The millions of people from Colorado who voted both for and against this are not wildlife biologists. They do not understand the implications or impacts. They have no grasp of the data or understanding of the research because they are not qualified to interpret them.⁣
⁣
It all comes down to the problem of letting that 𝗣𝗣 decide. 👀⁣
⁣
When you let 𝗣𝗼𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗰𝗶𝗮𝗻𝘀 and the 𝗣𝘂𝗯𝗹𝗶𝗰 make decisions that should be left up to the educated professionals in a particular field, you lose.⁣
⁣
So, what do I 𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 think of the reintroduction of wolves to Colorado?⁣
⁣
That decision should have been left in the capable, educated hands of Colorado’s wildlife biologist. It should have been decided by those who have dedicated their lives to the science of understanding that ecosystem.⁣
⁣
Karen from down the street should not have given the ability to let her feelings vote for it. Kenny from the outskirts of town shouldn’t have been given the opportunity to vote against it.⁣
⁣
There shouldn’t have been a vote at all.⁣
⁣
It should have been decided by the science.⁣
⁣
...and that is my nickel’s worth of opinion.⁣
⁣
𝗗𝗮𝘁𝗮 > 𝗙𝗲𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀⁣
